Ritter objects that we do not hear elsewhere that the Pythagoreans abstained from leeks and onions. Horace does not imply that they did, but only that in eating them they thought they were destroying living beings. They would have had little enough to live on, if they had abstained srom everything which involved the death of either animal or vegetable. His own notion that Horace is asking Iccius to employ Grosphus in catching fish and gathering onions as part of thesrnctus Agrippae is not likely to find many supporters.
